<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Line Length" class="currentChild" href="Line_Length">Line Length</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In typography, the overall width of a typeset line, usually the area between two margins. Also called <em>measure</em>, <em>column width</em>, or <em>line measure</em>. There are several long-held rules for establishing line length (essentially a function of <a title="Point Size" href="Point_Size">point size</a>) that ensure maximum <a title="Legibility" href="Legibility">legibility</a>. The following chart indicates the recommended line lengths (in points) for a variety of common text point sizes: 
</p>
<p id="l5">
[insert T012] 
</p>
<p id="l7">
Sometimes the formula <em>point size x 2</em> is used to determine the optimum line length. <em>Lowercase alphabet x 1.5</em> is also used. For maximum legibility, a line should comprise 55:60 characters, or 9:10 words. 
</p>
<p id="l9">
Wider typefaces look best with wider line lengths; condensed faces look best with narrow line lengths. Instead of wide line lengths, double or multiple columns of smaller line lengths should be used. 
</p>
